# LWC Form Patterns

## Labels: Use Built-in `label` Attribute

**Never** use separate `<label for="...">` elements with Lightning base components. LWC transforms IDs at render time, so `for`/`id` associations break—causing accessibility errors and "label's for attribute doesn't match any element id" warnings in DevTools.

Use the component's built-in `label` attribute instead. The component handles programmatic association correctly.

```html
<!-- ❌ BAD: Separate label breaks in LWC -->
<label class="slds-form-element__label" for="deal-name">Deal Name</label>
<lightning-input id="deal-name" data-field="dealName" ...></lightning-input>

<!-- ✅ GOOD: Built-in label -->
<lightning-input label="Deal Name" data-field="dealName" ...></lightning-input>
```

Applies to: `lightning-input`, `lightning-combobox`, `lightning-textarea`, `lightning-dual-listbox` (uses `label`).

## Multi-Column Form Layout: Row-Based CSS Grid

For forms with multiple columns, use **row-based CSS Grid** so fields align vertically across columns. Avoid stacked `slds-col` divs—they cause misaligned rows.

```css
.form-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 0 1rem;
    row-gap: 0.5rem;
}
```

```html
<div class="form-grid">
    <div class="slds-form-element"><lightning-input label="Deal Name" ...></lightning-input></div>
    <div class="slds-form-element"><lightning-input label="Parent ID" ...></lightning-input></div>
    <!-- Grid flows left-to-right, top-to-bottom; fields align across columns -->
</div>
```

Variants: `form-grid-2` (2 cols), `form-grid-3` (3 cols). Use `form-grid-span-2` for fields that span multiple columns (e.g. dual-listbox).

## Label-to-Input Spacing

The built-in `label` on Lightning components provides proper spacing. Avoid wrapping components in extra label wrappers—that creates double structure and excessive gaps.
